      <!-- INFO CARDS -->
      <div class="cards">
        <div class="panel">
          <div class="panel-head"><span class="idx">06</span><h2>Chlorine / CYA &amp; Shock</h2></div>
          <div class="panel-body" id="fccya"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="panel">
          <div class="panel-head"><span class="idx">07</span><h2>How the chemicals interact</h2></div>
          <div class="panel-body relations">
            <div class="r"><span class="ic">TA-pH</span><span><b>Alkalinity buffers pH.</b> Fix alkalinity first. With it out of range, pH won't hold and you'll chase it every visit.</span></div>
            <div class="r"><span class="ic">ACID</span><span><b>Muriatic acid lowers pH and alkalinity together.</b> To drop alkalinity without tanking pH, add acid in one spot, then aerate.</span></div>
            <div class="r"><span class="ic">ASH</span><span><b>Soda ash raises pH and nudges alkalinity up.</b> If only alkalinity is low, use baking soda instead. It lifts alkalinity with a much smaller pH bump.</span></div>
            <div class="r"><span class="ic">pH-ORP</span><span><b>ORP is pH-dependent.</b> Low pH inflates the ORP reading, and high pH deflates it, so ORP can look fine while free chlorine is actually low.</span></div>
            <div class="r"><span class="ic">CYA-Cl</span><span><b>More stabilizer means you must hold more chlorine,</b> and it also suppresses ORP. Keep free chlorine near 7.5% of the CYA reading.</span></div>
            <div class="r"><span class="ic">pH-Cl</span><span><b>High pH weakens chlorine.</b> Above pH 8.0 chlorine loses roughly half its punch, so balance pH before blaming the sanitizer.</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SAFETY -->
      <div class="panel" style="margin-top:22px">
        <div class="panel-head"><span class="idx">08</span><h2>Handling rules</h2></div>
        <div class="panel-body">
          <ul class="safety" style="margin:0;padding-left:18px">
            <li><b>Add acid to water, never water to acid.</b> Dilute muriatic in a bucket; add in the deep end, away from lights and skimmers.</li>
            <li><b>Never mix chemicals.</b> Cal-hypo and trichlor mixed dry is a fire and explosion hazard. Keep acid and chlorine additions hours apart with full circulation.</li>
            <li><b>Pump running, one dose at a time.</b> Wait about 15 to 30 minutes between different chemicals; retest 4 to 6 hours after dosing before adding more.</li>
            <li><b>Never shock with pH or alkalinity out of range,</b> and don't dose blind; test first, every time.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
